    "## Scaling\n",
    "A scalar is essentially any single digit number. We can use scalars to stretch or shrink vectors. Vector scaling is pairwise. In other words, when a vector is scaled by some scaler, a, the output vector is a list of the products of each element in the input vector with the scalar. In other words: $$ 2 \\begin{bmatrix} x_1 \\\\ x_2 \\\\ x_3 \\\\ \\vdots \\\\ x_n\\end{bmatrix} = \\begin{bmatrix} 2x_1 \\\\ 2x_2 \\\\ 2x_3 \\\\ \\vdots \\\\ 2x_n \\end{bmatrix}$$\n",
    "In this coding exercise, your goal is to multiply a vector by a scalar and visualize it using matplotlib.pyplot.subplots and matplotlib.pyplot.quiver!"
